[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] Bayesian neural networks are a particular type of Bayesian network that results from treating deep learning and artificial neural network models probabilistically, and assigning a prior distribution to their parameters.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] Computation in artificial neural networks is usually organized into sequential layers of artificial neurons.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] The number of neurons in a layer is called the layer width.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] As layer width grows large, many Bayesian neural networks reduce to a Gaussian process with a closed form compositional kernel.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] This Gaussian process is called the Neural Network Gaussian Process (NNGP) (not to be confused with the Nearest Neighbor Gaussian Process ).
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] It allows predictions from Bayesian neural networks to be more efficiently evaluated, and provides an analytic tool to understand deep learning models.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes have found increasing applications in many domains of the natural sciences due to their statistical modelling properties.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] Molecular property prediction has employed these process models in small molecular datasets due to their inference capabilities and computational costs.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] They are also being increasingly used as surrogate models for force field optimization.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes have also found extensive use in astrophysical and astronomical settings.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes can model correlated noise, a specific type of non-Gaussian noise dependent on some underlying unknown distribution correlated with observed values.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] This type of noise is often present in astronomical signals as instrumental systematics or as intrinsic to the observed object as a result of physical processes.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] Correlated noise is often a consideration for exoplanet transit events, and Gaussian processes have been used to de-trend these transit light curves (at timescales greater than that of the transit) to allow detection of weaker, more short-lived signals.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] These processes have also been used to disentangle planetary signals from stellar activity indicators inside radial velocity data, another method of exoplanet detection.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] Correlated noise produced by active regions on a star's photosphere (as a result of magnetic field interactions) can be of similar timescales as transit events, and Gaussian process models which handle sparsely sampled data are used to confirm exoplanet detections especially around young stars.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] The variability of rotating, magnetically active Sun-like stars can be modeled fairly accurately using Gaussian processes.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] This covariance function allows for the limited but feasible determination of stellar periods as a result of parameter $\lambda _{1}$ but lacks physical information about where these active regions are on the star observed.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes are also used in the analysis of individual and populations of active galactic nuclei (AGNs) due to their stochastic variability in the optical and radio parts of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] Damped random walk kernels in particular have previously been used to identify the extent of broad-line emission regions around supermassive black holes using reverberation mapping, and these kernels can also be used to characterize light curve variations for large AGN populations.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] Other astrophysical applications of Gaussian processes include models for pulsar timing and dispersion measure, gravitational wave structure and detector uncertainty (notably in the LIGO-Virgo-KAGRA collaboration), transient classification, and quasi-periodic oscillations.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] In practical applications, Gaussian process models are often evaluated on a grid leading to multivariate normal distributions.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] Using these models for prediction or parameter estimation using maximum likelihood requires evaluating a multivariate Gaussian density, which involves calculating the determinant and the inverse of the covariance matrix.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] Both of these operations have cubic computational complexity which means that even for grids of modest sizes, both operations can have a prohibitive computational cost.
[src:gaussian-process/gaussian-process] This drawback led to the development of multiple approximation methods.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] In machine learning, **kernel machines** are a class of algorithms for pattern analysis, whose best known member is the support-vector machine (SVM).
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] These methods involve using linear classifiers to solve nonlinear problems.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] The general task of pattern analysis is to find and study general types of relations (for example clusters, rankings, principal components, correlations, classifications) in datasets.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] The feature map in kernel machines is infinite dimensional but only requires a finite dimensional matrix from user-input according to the representer theorem.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Kernel machines are slow to compute for datasets larger than a couple of thousand examples without parallel processing.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] This operation is often computationally cheaper than the explicit computation of the coordinates.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] This approach is called the "**kernel trick**".
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Kernel functions have been introduced for sequence data, graphs, text, images, as well as vectors.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Algorithms capable of operating with kernels include the kernel perceptron, support-vector machines (SVM), Gaussian processes, principal components analysis (PCA), canonical correlation analysis, ridge regression, spectral clustering, linear adaptive filters and many others.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Most kernel algorithms are based on convex optimization or eigenproblems and are statistically well-founded.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Typically, their statistical properties are analyzed using statistical learning theory (for example, using Rademacher complexity).
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Kernel methods can be thought of as instance-based learners: rather than learning some fixed set of parameters corresponding to the features of their inputs, they instead "remember" the i -th training example $(\mathbf {x} _{i},y_{i})$ and learn for it a corresponding weight $w_{i}$ .
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Prediction for unlabeled inputs, i.e., those not in the training set, are treated by the application of a similarity function k , called a **kernel**, between the unlabeled input $\mathbf {x'}$ and each of the training inputs $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ .
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Kernel classifiers were described as early as the 1960s, with the invention of the kernel perceptron.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] They rose to great prominence with the popularity of the support-vector machine (SVM) in the 1990s, when the SVM was found to be competitive with neural networks on tasks such as handwriting recognition.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] The kernel trick avoids the explicit mapping that is needed to get linear learning algorithms to learn a nonlinear function or decision boundary.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] For all $\mathbf {x}$ and $\mathbf {x'}$ in the input space ${\mathcal {X}}$ , certain functions $k(\mathbf {x} ,\mathbf {x'} )$ can be expressed as an inner product in another space ${\mathcal {V}}$ .
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] The function $k\colon {\mathcal {X}}\times {\mathcal {X}}\to \mathbb {R}$ is often referred to as a *kernel* or a *kernel function*.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] The word "kernel" is used in mathematics to denote a weighting function for a weighted sum or integral.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Certain problems in machine learning have more structure than an arbitrary weighting function k .
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] On the other hand, an explicit representation for $\varphi$ is not necessary, as long as ${\mathcal {V}}$ is an inner product space.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] The alternative follows from Mercer's theorem: an implicitly defined function $\varphi$ exists whenever the space ${\mathcal {X}}$ can be equipped with a suitable measure ensuring the function k satisfies Mercer's condition.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Mercer's theorem is similar to a generalization of the result from linear algebra that associates an inner product to any positive-definite matrix.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] In fact, Mercer's condition can be reduced to this simpler case.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Some algorithms that depend on arbitrary relationships in the native space ${\mathcal {X}}$ would, in fact, have a linear interpretation in a different setting: the range space of $\varphi$ .
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] The linear interpretation gives us insight about the algorithm.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Furthermore, there is often no need to compute $\varphi$ directly during computation, as is the case with support-vector machines.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Some cite this running time shortcut as the primary benefit.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Researchers also use it to justify the meanings and properties of existing algorithms.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Theoretically, a Gram matrix $\mathbf {K} \in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ with respect to $\{\mathbf {x} _{1},\dotsc ,\mathbf {x} _{n}\}$ (sometimes also called a "kernel matrix"), where $K_{ij}=k(\mathbf {x} _{i},\mathbf {x} _{j})$ , must be positive semi-definite (PSD).
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Empirically, for machine learning heuristics, choices of a function k that do not satisfy Mercer's condition may still perform reasonably if k at least approximates the intuitive idea of similarity.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Regardless of whether k is a Mercer kernel, k may still be referred to as a "kernel".
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] If the kernel function k is also a covariance function as used in Gaussian processes, then the Gram matrix $\mathbf {K}$ can also be called a covariance matrix.
[src:gaussian-process/kernel-method] Application areas of kernel methods are diverse and include geostatistics, kriging, inverse distance weighting, 3D reconstruction, bioinformatics, cheminformatics, information extraction and handwriting recognition.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] The first meaning of *nonparametric* involves techniques that do not rely on data belonging to any particular parametric family of probability distributions.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] An example is order statistics, which are based on ordinal ranking of observations.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] The discussion following is taken from *Kendall's Advanced Theory of Statistics*.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] The second meaning of *nonparametric* involves techniques that do not assume that the *structure* of a model is fixed.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Typically, the model grows in size to accommodate the complexity of the data.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] In these techniques, individual variables *are* typically assumed to belong to parametric distributions, and assumptions about the types of associations among variables are also made.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Nonparametric methods are widely used for studying populations that have a ranked order (such as movie reviews receiving one to five "stars").
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] The use of nonparametric methods may be necessary when data have a ranking but no clear numerical interpretation, such as when assessing preferences.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] In terms of levels of measurement, nonparametric methods result in ordinal data.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] As nonparametric methods make fewer assumptions, their applicability is much more general than the corresponding parametric methods.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] In particular, they may be applied in situations where less is known about the application in question.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Also, due to the reliance on fewer assumptions, nonparametric methods are more robust.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Nonparametric methods are sometimes considered simpler to use and more robust than parametric methods, even when the assumptions of parametric methods are justified.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] This is due to their more general nature, which may make them less susceptible to misuse and misunderstanding.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Nonparametric methods can be considered a conservative choice, as they will work even when their assumptions are not met, whereas parametric methods can produce misleading results when their assumptions are violated.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] The wider applicability and increased robustness of nonparametric tests comes at a cost: in cases where a parametric test's assumptions are met, nonparametric tests have less statistical power.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] In other words, a larger sample size can be required to draw conclusions with the same degree of confidence.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] In mathematical statistics, nonparametric models are considered models that do not rely on a parametric assumption of the unknown data distribution (in density estimation problems) or of the regression function (in regression problems).
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] While the goal of any parametric model is the estimation of a finite number of parameters $\theta _{1},\dots ,\theta _{p}\in \mathbb {R}$ , nonparametric models aim to directly estimate the data distribution/regression function.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Relevant questions in this field regard the construction of reasonable estimators, consistency, rates of convergence and their optimality, and adaptive estimation.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] As in parametric statistics, a desirable property for an estimator ${\hat {f_{n}}}$ is that it converges to the target function f as the sample size n goes to infinity, that is, the approximation error converges to zero.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Usually, the approximation is measured in terms of $L^{2}$ -norm distance between ${\hat {f_{n}}}$ and f .
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] If an estimator is consistent for all square-integrable f , then it is called **universally consistent**.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Many common nonparametric estimators are weakly universally consistent, for example, the Nadarya-Watson estimator, kNNs and certain local polynomial estimators.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] A central topic in the statistical analysis of nonparametric estimators is their speed of convergence towards the true target function f and whether the speed is optimal, i.e., the convergence is as fast as possible.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] The most common way to measure the speed of convergence of an estimator is the minimax convergence rate, which considers the expected loss of the estimator in the worst case scenario.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Under certain assumptions on the smoothness of f , one can show that there is a minimal convergence rates that no estimator can undercut, and so any estimator achieving this minimal rate is called optimal.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] The detailed analysis of nonparametric estimators then separates into the estimation of probability densities and regressions functions.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Minimax lower bounds are known for different pairs of function classes ${\mathcal {F}}$ and comparison metrics L .
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] In fact, the Hölder spaces and the Sobolev spaces are special cases of some Besov spaces, namely $C^{\alpha }({\mathcal {X}})=B_{\infty ,\infty }^{\alpha }({\mathcal {X}})$ for $\alpha \notin \mathbb {Z}$ and $H^{s}({\mathcal {X}})=B_{2,2}^{s}({\mathcal {X}})$ .
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Thus, it often suffices to derive lower bounds under Besov-smoothness assumptions.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] By Scheffé's theorem, the total variation distance $\mathrm {TV} (\mathbb {P} _{f},\mathbb {P} _{g})$ is equivalent to the $L^{1}$ -distance of f and g .
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] The nonparametric rate is thus slower than the parametric rate $n^{-1}$ , especially in large dimensions, and approaches the parametric rate as the smoothness of the density tends to infinity.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Kernel density estimators, for instance, achieve the lower bound w.r.t. the MISE under a Sobolev hypothesis class under an appropriate bandwidth choice and is thus minimax optimal.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] More recently, also score-based generative models have been shown to achieve minimax convergence rates in total variation and in Wasserstein-1 distance for $B_{p,q}^{s}([0,1]^{d})$ -smooth distributions, $s>(1/p-1/2)_{+}$ , that are bounded away from zero from below.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Typically, the independent variables $X_{i}$ are assumed to have values in the unit cube $[0,1]^{d}$ and to be either determinsitic points on a grid (deterministic design) or uniformly distributed (random design).
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] The above setting applies to binary classification as well.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Indeed, many classification methods are of that form, for example logistic regression, linear discriminant analysis, quadratic discriminant analysis, and k-nearest-neighbors, and support vector machines.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Under certain technical assumptions, the following lower bounds are known.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Instead, one is interested in methods that achieve the minimax optimal convergence rates not only for one specific smoothness parameter, but across different values.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Adaptive estimators are often realized by taking estimators that are minimax optimal for a family of hypothesis classes and by estimating the hyperparameters via a higher-level procedure, such as unbiased risk estimation or cross-validation.
[src:gaussian-process/nonparametric-statistics] Early nonparametric statistics include the median (13th century or earlier, use in estimation by Edward Wright, 1599; see Median § History) and the sign test by John Arbuthnot (1710) in analyzing the human sex ratio at birth (see Sign test § History).
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The most common form of regression analysis is linear regression, in which one finds the line (or a more complex linear combination) that most closely fits the data according to a specific mathematical criterion.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] For example, the method of ordinary least squares computes the unique line (or hyperplane) that minimizes the sum of squared differences between the true data and that line (or hyperplane).
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] For specific mathematical reasons (see linear regression), this allows the researcher to estimate the conditional expectation (or population average value) of the dependent variable when the independent variables take on a given set of values.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Less common forms of regression use slightly different procedures to estimate alternative location parameters (e.g., quantile regression or Necessary Condition Analysis) or estimate the conditional expectation across a broader collection of non-linear models (e.g., nonparametric regression).
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Regression analysis is primarily used for two conceptually distinct purposes.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] First, regression analysis is widely used for prediction and forecasting, where its use has substantial overlap with the field of machine learning.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Second, in some situations regression analysis can be used to infer causal relationships between the independent and dependent variables.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Importantly, regressions by themselves only reveal relationships between a dependent variable and a collection of independent variables in a fixed dataset.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] To use regressions for prediction or to infer causal relationships, respectively, a researcher must carefully justify why existing relationships have predictive power for a new context or why a relationship between two variables has a causal interpretation.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The latter is especially important when researchers hope to estimate causal relationships using observational data.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] He also distinguished between two inhomogeneous sets of data and might have thought of an *optimal* solution in terms of bias, though not in terms of effectiveness." He previously used an averaging method in his 1671 work on Newton's rings, which was unprecedented at the time.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The method of least squares was published by Legendre in 1805, and by Gauss in 1809.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Legendre and Gauss both applied the method to the problem of determining, from astronomical observations, the orbits of bodies about the Sun (mostly comets, but also later the then newly discovered minor planets).
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Gauss published a further development of the theory of least squares in 1821, including a version of the Gauss–Markov theorem.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The term "regression" was coined by Francis Galton in the 19th century to describe a biological phenomenon.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The phenomenon was that the heights of descendants of tall ancestors tend to regress down towards a normal average (a phenomenon also known as regression toward the mean).
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] For Galton, regression had only this biological meaning, but his work was later extended by Udny Yule and Karl Pearson to a more general statistical context.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] In the work of Yule and Pearson, the joint distribution of the response and explanatory variables is assumed to be Gaussian.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Fisher assumed that the conditional distribution of the response variable is Gaussian, but the joint distribution need not be.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] In this respect, Fisher's assumption is closer to Gauss's formulation of 1821.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] In the 1950s and 1960s, economists used electromechanical desk calculators to calculate regressions.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Before 1970, it sometimes took up to 24 hours to receive the result from one regression.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Regression methods continue to be an area of active research.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Modern regression analysis is typically done with statistical and spreadsheet software packages on computers as well as on handheld scientific and graphing calculators.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] In practice, researchers first select a model they would like to estimate and then use their chosen method (e.g., ordinary least squares) to estimate the parameters of that model.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] In various fields of application, different terminologies are used in place of dependent and independent variables.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] In the standard regression model, the independent variables $X_{i}$ are assumed to be free of error.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The errors-in-variables model can be used if the independent variables are assumed to contain errors.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Other modifications to the standard regression model can be made to account for various scenarios, such as situations involving omitted variables, confounding variables or endogeneity.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The researchers' goal is to estimate the function $f(X_{i},\beta )$ that most closely fits the data.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] To carry out regression analysis, the form of the function f must be specified.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Sometimes the form of this function is based on knowledge about the relationship between $Y_{i}$ and $X_{i}$ that does not rely on the data.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] If no such knowledge is available, a flexible or convenient form for f is chosen.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] For example, a simple univariate regression may propose $f(X_{i},\beta )=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{i}$ , suggesting that the researcher believes $Y_{i}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{i}+e_{i}$ to be a reasonable approximation for the statistical process generating the data.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Once researchers determine their preferred statistical model, different forms of regression analysis provide tools to estimate the parameters $\beta$ .
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] For example, least squares (including its most common variant, ordinary least squares) finds the value of $\beta$ that minimizes the sum of squared errors $\sum _{i}(Y_{i}-f(X_{i},\beta ))^{2}$ .
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] A given regression method will ultimately provide an estimate of $\beta$ , usually denoted ${\hat {\beta }}$ to distinguish the estimate from the true (unknown) parameter value that generated the data.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Using this estimate, the researcher can then use the *fitted value* ${\hat {Y_{i}}}=f(X_{i},{\hat {\beta }})$ for prediction or to assess the accuracy of the model in explaining the data.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Whether the researcher is intrinsically interested in the estimate ${\hat {\beta }}$ or the predicted value ${\hat {Y_{i}}}$ will depend on context and their goals.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] As described in ordinary least squares, least squares is widely used because the estimated function $f(X_{i},{\hat {\beta }})$ approximates the conditional expectation $E(Y_{i}|X_{i})$ .
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] However, alternative variants (e.g., least absolute deviations or quantile regression) are useful when researchers want to model other functions $f(X_{i},\beta )$ .
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] There must be sufficient data to estimate a regression model.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] For example, suppose that a researcher has access to N rows of data with one dependent and two independent variables: $(Y_{i},X_{1i},X_{2i})$ .
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Suppose further that the researcher wants to estimate a bivariate linear model via least squares: $Y_{i}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{1i}+\beta _{2}X_{2i}+e_{i}$ .
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] To understand why there are infinitely many options, note that the system of $N=2$ equations is to be solved for 3 unknowns, which makes the system underdetermined.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Alternatively, one can visualize infinitely many 3-dimensional planes that go through $N=2$ fixed points.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] More generally, to estimate a least squares model with k distinct parameters, one must have $N\geq k$ distinct data points.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] If $N>k$ , then there does not generally exist a set of parameters that will perfectly fit the data.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The quantity $N-k$ appears often in regression analysis, and is referred to as the degrees of freedom in the model.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Moreover, to estimate a least squares model, the independent variables $(X_{1i},X_{2i},...,X_{ki})$ must be linearly independent: one must *not* be able to reconstruct any of the independent variables by adding and multiplying the remaining independent variables.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] As discussed in ordinary least squares, this condition ensures that $X^{T}X$ is an invertible matrix and therefore that a unique solution ${\hat {\beta }}$ exists.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] By itself, a regression is just a computation performed on a set of data.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] In order to interpret the resultant regression as a meaningful statistical model that quantifies real-world relationships, researchers often rely on a number of classical assumptions.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] A handful of conditions are sufficient for the least-squares estimator to possess desirable properties: in particular, the Gauss–Markov assumptions imply that the parameter estimates will be unbiased, consistent, and efficient in the class of linear unbiased estimators.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Practitioners have developed a variety of methods to maintain some or all of these desirable properties in real-world settings, because these classical assumptions are unlikely to hold exactly.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] For example, modeling errors-in-variables can lead to reasonable estimates independent variables are measured with errors.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Heteroscedasticity-consistent standard errors allow the variance of $e_{i}$ to change across values of $X_{i}$ .
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Correlated errors that exist within subsets of the data or follow specific patterns can be handled using *clustered standard errors, geographic weighted regression*, or Newey–West standard errors, among other techniques.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] When rows of data correspond to locations in space, the choice of how to model $e_{i}$ within geographic units can have important consequences.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The subfield of econometrics is largely focused on developing techniques that allow researchers to make reasonable real-world conclusions in real-world settings, where classical assumptions do not hold exactly.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] In linear regression, the model specification is that the dependent variable, $y_{i}$ is a linear combination of the *parameters* (but need not be linear in the *independent variables*).
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] In multiple linear regression, there are several independent variables or functions of independent variables.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] In both cases, $\varepsilon _{i}$ is an error term and the subscript i indexes a particular observation.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The residual, $e_{i}=y_{i}-{\widehat {y}}_{i}$ , is the difference between the value of the dependent variable predicted by the model, ${\widehat {y}}_{i}$ , and the true value of the dependent variable, $y_{i}$ .
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] One method of estimation is ordinary least squares.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Minimization of this function results in a set of normal equations, a set of simultaneous linear equations in the parameters, which are solved to yield the parameter estimators, ${\widehat {\beta }}_{0},{\widehat {\beta }}_{1}$ .
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] where ${\bar {x}}$ is the mean (average) of the x values and ${\bar {y}}$ is the mean of the y values.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] This is called the mean square error (MSE) of the regression.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The denominator is the sample size reduced by the number of model parameters estimated from the same data, $(n-p)$ for p regressors or $(n-p-1)$ if an intercept is used.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] In this case, $p=1$ so the denominator is $n-2$ .
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Under the further assumption that the population error term is normally distributed, the researcher can use these estimated standard errors to create confidence intervals and conduct hypothesis tests about the population parameters.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] where $x_{ij}$ is the i -th observation on the j -th independent variable.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] If the first independent variable takes the value 1 for all i , $x_{i1}=1$ , then $\beta _{1}$ is called the regression intercept.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The least squares parameter estimates are obtained from p normal equations.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] where the $ij$ element of $\mathbf {X}$ is $x_{ij}$ , the i element of the column vector Y is $y_{i}$ , and the j element of ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}$ is ${\hat {\beta }}_{j}$ .
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Once a regression model has been constructed, it may be important to confirm the goodness of fit of the model and the statistical significance of the estimated parameters.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Commonly used checks of goodness of fit include the R-squared, analyses of the pattern of residuals and hypothesis testing.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Statistical significance can be checked by an F-test of the overall fit, followed by t-tests of individual parameters.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Interpretations of these diagnostic tests rest heavily on the model's assumptions.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Although examination of the residuals can be used to invalidate a model, the results of a t-test or F-test are sometimes more difficult to interpret if the model's assumptions are violated.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] For example, if the error term does not have a normal distribution, in small samples the estimated parameters will not follow normal distributions and complicate inference.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] With relatively large samples, however, a central limit theorem can be invoked such that hypothesis testing may proceed using asymptotic approximations.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Limited dependent variables, which are response variables that are categorical or constrained to fall only in a certain range, often arise in econometrics.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The response variable may be non-continuous ("limited" to lie on some subset of the real line).
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] For binary (zero or one) variables, if analysis proceeds with least-squares linear regression, the model is called the linear probability model.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Nonlinear models for binary dependent variables include the probit and logit model.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The multivariate probit model is a standard method of estimating a joint relationship between several binary dependent variables and some independent variables.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] For categorical variables with more than two values there is the multinomial logit.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] For ordinal variables with more than two values, there are the ordered logit and ordered probit models.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Censored regression models may be used when the dependent variable is only sometimes observed, and Heckman correction type models may be used when the sample is not randomly selected from the population of interest.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] An alternative to such procedures is linear regression based on polychoric correlation (or polyserial correlations) between the categorical variables.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Such procedures differ in the assumptions made about the distribution of the variables in the population.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] If the variable is positive with low values and represents the repetition of the occurrence of an event, then count models like the Poisson regression or the negative binomial model may be used.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] When the model function is not linear in the parameters, the sum of squares must be minimized by an iterative procedure.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] This introduces many complications which are summarized in Differences between linear and non-linear least squares.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Regression models ***predict*** a value of the *Y* variable given known values of the *X* variables.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Prediction *within* the range of values in the dataset used for model-fitting is known informally as *interpolation*.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Prediction *outside* this range of the data is known as *extrapolation*.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Performing extrapolation relies strongly on the regression assumptions.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The further the extrapolation goes outside the data, the more room there is for the model to fail due to differences between the assumptions and the sample data or the true values.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] A *prediction interval* that represents the uncertainty may accompany the point prediction.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Such intervals tend to expand rapidly as the values of the independent variable(s) moved outside the range covered by the observed data.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] For such reasons and others, some tend to say that it might be unwise to undertake extrapolation.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The assumption of a particular form for the relation between *Y* and *X* is another source of uncertainty.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] A properly conducted regression analysis will include an assessment of how well the assumed form is matched by the observed data, but it can only do so within the range of values of the independent variables actually available.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] This means that any extrapolation is particularly reliant on the assumptions being made about the structural form of the regression relationship.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] If this knowledge includes the fact that the dependent variable cannot go outside a certain range of values, this can be made use of in selecting the model – even if the observed dataset has no values particularly near such bounds.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] The implications of this step of choosing an appropriate functional form for the regression can be great when extrapolation is considered.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] At a minimum, it can ensure that any extrapolation arising from a fitted model is "realistic" (or in accord with what is known).
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] There are no generally agreed methods for relating the number of observations versus the number of independent variables in the model.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] One method conjectured by Good and Hardin is $N=m^{n}$ , where N is the sample size, n is the number of independent variables and m is the number of observations needed to reach the desired precision if the model had only one independent variable.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] For example, a researcher is building a linear regression model using a dataset that contains 1000 patients ( N ).
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] All major statistical software packages perform least squares regression analysis and inference.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Simple linear regression and multiple regression using least squares can be done in some spreadsheet applications and on some calculators.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] While many statistical software packages can perform various types of nonparametric and robust regression, these methods are less standardized.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Different software packages implement different methods, and a method with a given name may be implemented differently in different packages.
[src:gaussian-process/regression-analysis] Specialized regression software has been developed for use in fields such as survey analysis and neuroimaging.
